lead_paragraph: Many in Egypt are baffled by the scale of a clampdown aimed at preventing any protest commemorating the Jan. 25, 2011, uprising that toppled former President Hosni Mubarak.

byline.contributor: Amina Ismail contributed reporting from Cairo.

headline.print_headline: Crackdown by Egypt Draws Attention to an Anniversary It Aimed to Avoid
headline.main: Crackdown by Egypt Draws Attention to an Anniversary It Aimed to Avoid

snippet: Many in Egypt are baffled by the scale of a clampdown aimed at preventing any protest commemorating the Jan. 25, 2011, uprising that toppled former President Hosni Mubarak.
abstract: Egyptian authorities raid Cairo cultural venues in crackdown aimed at preventing unrest ahead of 5th anniversary of toppling of Pres Hosni Mubarak; observers perplexed by scale of government's security response suspect it may be motivated less by fears of public impatience than by anxiety surrounding security forces' grim memories of their catastrophic loss of control in 2011 uprising.
